{"id":"1801.02162","submitter":"Elena Arseneva","authors":"Elena Arseneva, Prosenjit Bose, Jean-Lou De Carufel, Sander\n  Verdonschot","title":"Reconstructing a convex polygon from its $\\omega$-cloud","comments":"16 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An $\\omega$-wedge is the closed set of points contained between two rays that\nare emanating from a single point (the apex), and are separated by an angle\n$\\omega < \\pi$. Given a convex polygon $P$, we place the $\\omega$-wedge such\nthat $P$ is inside the wedge and both rays are tangent to $P$. The set of apex\npositions of all such placements of the $\\omega$-wedge is called the\n$\\omega$-cloud of $P$.\n  We investigate reconstructing a polygon $P$ from its $\\omega$-cloud. Previous\nwork on reconstructing $P$ from probes with the $\\omega$-wedge required\nknowledge of the points of tangency between $P$ and the two rays of the\n$\\omega$-wedge in addition to the location of the apex. Here we consider the\nsetting where the maximal $\\omega$-cloud alone is given. We give two conditions\nunder which it uniquely defines $P$: (i) when $\\omega < \\pi$ is fixed/given, or\n(ii) when what is known is that $\\omega < \\pi/2$. We show that if neither of\nthese two conditions hold, then $P$ may not be unique. We show that, when the\nuniqueness conditions hold, the polygon $P$ can be reconstructed in $O(n)$ time\nwith $O(1)$ working space in addition to the input, where $n$ is the number of\narcs in the input $\\omega$-cloud.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 7 Jan 2018 09:14:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 19 Feb 2018 12:04:45 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 20 Mar 2019 10:57:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-03-21"}
